<methodology slug="cost-estimation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Bottom-up estimation from WBS with PERT uncertainty, risk-driven contingency, and management reserve. Output is defensible Cost Baseline and Budget at Completion.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>estimation</tag>
      <tag>budget</tag>
      <tag>cost-baseline</tag>
      <tag>wbs</tag>
      <tag>pert</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Cost Estimation</title>

    <summary>Structured approach to producing a defensible project cost baseline: bottom-up estimation from a WBS, three-point (PERT) uncertainty modelling, risk-driven contingency reserve, and a separate management reserve. Output is a Cost Baseline plus Budget at Completion (BAC), versioned through every change-control event.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Projects fail financially because estimates omit indirect costs, ignore scope growth, and use flat contingency percentages instead of risk-driven reserves. Three-point estimation makes uncertainty explicit; separating contingency (PM-controlled) from management reserve (sponsor-controlled) prevents double-spending and provides a clear audit trail when the budget is challenged.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Producing an initial budget for a feature, project, or RFP response.</item>
        <item>Bottom-up estimation from a WBS (each work package gets labor + tools + infra cost).</item>
        <item>Build-vs-buy / build-vs-SaaS decisions where opportunity cost must be quantified.</item>
        <item>Updating the cost baseline after a change-control event.</item>
        <item>Solopreneur "true cost" analysis — own time at market rate vs. out-of-pocket spend.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Agile teams estimating via story points + capacity-based run-rate — cost is derived from team-month spend, not bottom-up sums.</item>
        <item>Pre-discovery exploration where requirements are less than 30% defined — use ROM (rough order of magnitude, plus or minus 50%) instead; bottom-up output will be a fantasy.</item>
        <item>Fixed-fee contracts already signed — internal re-estimation has no contractual force and creates confusion.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="cost-categories">
      <title>Cost Categories and Framework</title>

      <rule>
        <statement>Classify every cost line into one of four categories before summing: direct, indirect, fixed, variable.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixing categories causes budget gaps; indirect costs (overhead, management) are the most-often forgotten and typically add 30-50% above direct labor.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Direct: salaries, contractors, software licenses. Indirect: office overhead, utilities, management loading. Fixed: base salaries, subscriptions. Variable: overtime, cloud usage, contractor hours.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="bottom-up-estimation">
      <title>Step 1: Bottom-Up Estimation</title>

      <rule>
        <statement>Estimate each WBS work package independently: identify roles, apply hours, multiply by fully-loaded rate (salary x 1.3-1.8 depending on tax jurisdiction).</statement>
        <rationale>Bottom-up is more accurate than analogical or parametric when scope is known; it forces explicit decomposition that surfaces missing work packages.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always cite the source of every rate (vendor quote, internal rate card version, market survey). Reject any estimate line that lacks a rate source.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs and humans both invent plausible rates; without a source the number cannot be defended or audited.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="three-point-estimation">
      <title>Step 2: Three-Point PERT Estimation</title>

      <rule>
        <statement>For uncertain cost lines, collect three estimates (Optimistic, Most Likely, Pessimistic) and compute Expected = (O + 4M + P) / 6.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-point estimates anchor on optimistic outcomes; PERT forces acknowledgment of the worst case and weights the most-likely scenario correctly.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>If Pessimistic / Most Likely is less than 1.8, flag the estimate for human review — pessimistic values are systematically underestimated.</statement>
        <rationale>Anchoring bias causes humans and LLMs to set pessimistic estimates too close to most-likely; a ratio below 1.8 is a signal the tail risk was not considered.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <note>Cloud hosting 3-point: O=$200/mo, M=$350/mo, P=$800/mo. Expected = (200 + 4x350 + 800) / 6 = $400/mo. Ratio P/M = 2.3, passes the review gate.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="contingency-reserve">
      <title>Step 3: Contingency Reserve (Known Unknowns)</title>

      <rule>
        <statement>Size contingency reserve using the risk register: sum each open risk's (probability x impact), then round up. Do not use a flat percentage.</statement>
        <rationale>Flat percentages (10-15%) ignore actual risk distribution; risk-driven reserves are defensible to sponsors and scale correctly with project uncertainty.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Guidance when no risk register exists: 10-15% for well-defined scope; 20-25% for innovative projects; 30-40% for high-uncertainty work. These are starting points, not substitutes for a register.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Contingency reserve is PM-controlled; document it in the Cost Baseline. Management reserve is sponsor-controlled and stays outside the baseline.</statement>
        <rationale>Blending the two removes the governance layer that protects the project from scope escalation without authorization.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cost-baseline-bac">
      <title>Step 4: Cost Baseline and BAC</title>

      <rule>
        <statement>Cost Baseline = Direct Costs + Indirect Costs + Contingency Reserve. BAC = Cost Baseline + Management Reserve.</statement>
        <rationale>Standard PMI formula; separating the two allows EVM tracking (CPI, SPI) against the baseline while keeping major-scope buffer separate.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Re-baseline at every approved change-control event; version the baseline with the change-request ID.</statement>
        <rationale>Never letting the original estimate persist past a scope change is the only way to maintain a valid audit trail.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="examples-antipatterns">
      <title>Examples and Anti-Patterns</title>

      <example type="good" title="SaaS MVP Phased Estimate">
        <note>Five-phase estimate: Discovery 2wks=$8,200; Design 2wks=$6,300; Development 8wks=$48,900; Testing 2wks=$8,300; Launch 1wk=$4,300. Subtotal=$76,000. Add 20% contingency=$15,200. Total=$91,200. Contingency sized at 20% because requirements are partially defined (innovative project band).</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Solopreneur Build-vs-Buy">
        <note>Build: 100 hours x $150 opportunity cost + $500 tools = $15,500. Buy: $99/mo x 12 + 5hr setup x $150 = $1,938. Decision: Buy unless building creates unique competitive advantage.</note>
      </example>

      <rule>
        <statement>For solopreneurs, treat own time at market hourly rate as an explicit cost line; never mark it as "free".</statement>
        <rationale>Opportunity cost is real; 100 hours at $150/hr = $15,000. A SaaS at $99/mo x 12 = $1,188 often wins once the line is visible.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Salary equals total cost — applying no overhead multiplier to labor.</description>
        <reason>Employer taxes, benefits, and facilities add 30-50% above salary. Omitting them produces a baseline that is structurally underfunded from day one.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Flat contingency percentage applied without a risk register.</description>
        <reason>15% on a $500K project with three high-probability risks is likely insufficient; 15% on a low-risk maintenance project is padding. Risk-driven reserves calibrate to actual exposure.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Fixed price contract with variable scope.</description>
        <reason>Any scope addition without a corresponding price increase produces silent budget erosion that neither party acknowledges until it becomes a dispute.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Single-point estimates with no uncertainty range.</description>
        <reason>Empirically, software estimates are systematically optimistic by 50-100%. Without a pessimistic case, the cost baseline has no resilience to the most-likely outcome.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Re-estimating but not re-baselining after a scope change.</description>
        <reason>The original baseline remains the reference; EVM metrics compare against it even though scope changed, making all variance numbers meaningless.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <title>Agentic Workflow and Integration</title>

      <p>The agent is a calculator + auditor, not a decision-maker. Feed it the WBS (work packages with effort hours), a labor rate card, an infra/tools list, and a risk register; it produces a structured cost estimate (direct, indirect, contingency, management reserve) plus a sensitivity analysis. A human approves the numbers before they enter the budget. Re-run the agent on every scope change to keep the baseline live.</p>

      <p>Inputs: wbs.yaml list of {id, name, effort_hours_optimistic, most_likely, pessimistic, role}. rates.yaml hourly rate per role (source: RFP / contract / internal). overhead: 0.3 (fully-loaded multiplier on labor). contingency: risk_register.yaml (use risk-driven, not flat %). duration_months: int. tools.yaml SaaS subscriptions in scope.</p>

      <p>Output JSON: direct_costs, indirect_costs, risk_driven_contingency_usd, management_reserve_usd, cost_baseline_usd, budget_at_completion_usd, sensitivity with p50, p80, p95, assumptions with explicit entries.</p>

      <p>Rules: No invented rates; cite source field. Round to nearest USD; never $X.XX precision spurious. If any input missing, return error not a guess.</p>

      <title>Recommended Subagents</title>

      <p>A cost-estimator subagent (define inline) — reads WBS + rate card YAML, outputs a cost-baseline JSON with PERT 3-point per work package.</p>

      <p>A sensitivity-analyzer subagent — Monte-Carlo over the 3-point distributions, returns P50 / P80 / P95 totals.</p>

      <p>faion-sdd-executor — when estimate becomes a task, drives implementation through quality gates.</p>

      <title>Limitations and Failure Modes</title>

      <p>Three-point estimation gives false precision: PERT mean assumes a beta distribution rarely true in software; pessimistic cost is consistently under-estimated by humans and LLMs. Contingency reserve sized as a flat percent ignores risk register; high-risk projects need risk-driven reserve, not 15%. Overhead loading varies wildly (1.3x for fully-loaded employee in low-tax markets, 1.8x+ in high-tax markets); a single multiplier is wrong by region. LLMs benchmark hourly rates from training data 12-24 months stale; current rates can differ by 30%+. Currency / FX volatility in multi-region projects is not captured by static numbers. Sunk-cost bias: re-estimates after work has started anchor on the original number.</p>

      <title>AI-Agent Gotchas</title>

      <p>LLMs invent rates ("senior dev: $150/hr") confidently. Force rate_source field per row; reject estimates without it. Pessimistic estimates are systematically too low (anchoring). Add a check: if p / m is less than 1.8, flag for human review. Triangular vs beta-PERT is conflated; results differ by approximately 20% on tails. Pick one and label it. Currency: agent outputs USD when WBS was in EUR. Force a currency field, fail if mixed. Overhead multiplier: 1.3x is North-America baseline; agents apply it globally. Parameterize per region. Contingency double-count: agent adds 15% AND a risk-driven reserve. Pick one strategy. Numerical hallucination: an LLM doing arithmetic on greater than 5 work packages drifts. Always do math in code (Python tool / spreadsheet API), not in prose. "Total budget" output sometimes excludes management reserve — always print Cost Baseline AND BAC. LLMs round inconsistently ($91,687 to "$92K"); for budget docs, keep raw and rounded both, label clearly.</p>

      <title>Best Practices</title>

      <p>Always quote the source of every rate (vendor quote, internal rate card v.X, market survey). No source = no rate. Use risk-driven contingency: each open risk x probability x impact, sum, round up. Beats flat 15%. Report P50 / P80 / P95, not just point estimate. Sponsor approves a P-level, not a number. Separate cost baseline (PM-controlled) from management reserve (sponsor-controlled). Do not blend. Track cost-baseline version with each change request — diff is the audit trail. For solopreneurs, opportunity cost = own hourly market rate (not "free"); buy options often win once you see the line. Re-baseline at every milestone gate; never let the original estimate persist past month 2 unchallenged. Kill the "fixed price + variable scope" pattern at proposal stage. Either fix scope or use T and M with cap.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/cost-worksheet.md" purpose="Full cost breakdown with direct, indirect, reserves, and BAC sections."/>
      <template path="templates/quick-estimate.md" purpose="Rapid labor + overhead + contingency formula for early-stage scoping."/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/pert_estimate.py" purpose="PERT mean, std-dev, P80, P95 from a WBS JSON with per-work-package 3-point hours + rate."/>
    </scripts>

    <see-also>
      <ref slug="earned-value-management"/>
